esarean section. The bleeding is painless and occurred without any trauma. Her vital signs are stable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete placental abruption","Placenta accreta","Partial placental abruption","Placenta previa","Vasa praevia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta previa\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with painless, bright red vaginal bleeding in the third trimester. Risk factors include previous caesarean section and multiparity, both present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other conditions can be distinguished:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete placental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with severe abdominal pain and dark bleeding, often with fetal compromise\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta accreta\u003C/strong\u003E is often associated with placenta previa but is usually diagnosed on ultrasound before bleeding occurs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial placental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E presents with painful vaginal bleeding and uterine tenderness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasa praevia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bleeding at the time of membrane rupture and results in rapid fetal compromise\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe absence of pain and the presence of risk factors strongly suggest placenta previa as the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Placenta previa occurs when the placenta implants in the lower uterine segment, partially or completely covering the internal cervical os.","Risk factors for placenta previa include previous caesarean section, multiparity, and advanced maternal age.","Placenta previa typically presents with painless vaginal bleeding in the third trimester."],"references":["Harper LM, Odibo AO, Macones GA, Crane JP, Cahill AG. Effect of placenta previa on fetal growth. Am J Obstet Gynecol. 2010 Oct;203(4):330.e1-5. doi: 10.1016/j.ajog.2010.05.014. PMID: 20599185; PMCID: PMC3128804.","Anderson-Bagga FM, Sze A. Placenta Previa. 2023 Jun 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30969640.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52769"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16088"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52769"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T20:01:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T20:01:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8779"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67317"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data